es for Asia’s Seas -- tAppendix B: Written-Down Oral Histories of the Swahili Coasts -- tAppendix C: Fieldwork Excerpt from Sana’a -- tAppendix D: Indian Spice Traders in India and Malaysia -- tAppendix E: Dutch East Indies Regulations with Local Maritime States -- tAppendix F: Chinese Marine Goods Traders in East and Southeast Asia -- tAppendix G: Chinese Marine Products Newspaper Clipping, Taipei, Taiwan -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA sweeping account of how the sea routes of Asia have transformed a vast expanse of the globe over the past five hundred years, powerfully shaping the modern worldIn the centuries leading up to our own, the volume of traffic across Asian sea routes—an area stretching from East Africa and the Middle East to Japan—grew dramatically, eventually making them the busiest in the world. The result was a massive circulation of people, commodities, religion, culture, technology, and ideas. In this book, Eric Tagliacozzo chronicles how the seas and oceans of Asia have shaped the history of the largest continent for the past half millennium, leaving an indelible mark on the modern world in the process.Paying special attention to migration, trade, the environment, and cities, In Asian Waters examines the long history of contact between China and East Africa; the spread of Hinduism and Buddhism across the Bay of Bengal; and the intertwined histories of Islam and Christianity in the Philippines. The book illustrates how India became central to the spice trade; how the Indian Ocean became a “British lake” between the seventeenth and nineteenth centuries; and how lighthouses and sea mapping played important roles in imperialism. The volume ends by asking what may happen if China comes to rule the waves of Asia, as Britain once did.A novel account showing how Asian history can be seen as a whole when seen from the water, In Asian Waters presents a voyage into a past that is still alive in the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aNavigationzAsiaxHistory. 0aOcean and civilization. 0aSeaszAsiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAlbertus Magnus.  aArchaeology.  aArea studies.  aArmenians.  aArt history.  aAstronomical object.  aAtlantic history.  aBody of water.  aBrunei.  aBuddhism.  aBureaucrat.  aCambridge University Press.  aCarrefour.  aCase study.  aChinese tea.  aChristianity and Islam.  aCircular orbit.  aCircumference.  aCivilisation (TV series).  aCommodity.  aConnections (TV series).  aCultural history.  aDavid Armitage (historian).  aDejima.  aDhow.  aEarly modern period.  aEast Africa.  aEastern Arabia.  aEmpire.  aEnvironmental history.  aEric Wolf.  aEurasian Steppe.  aFernand Braudel.  aForced conversion.  aGeography of Asia.  aGuangdong.  aGulf of Thailand.  aGupta.  aHeadhunting.  aHegemony.  aHinduism.  aHonolulu.  aIndian Ocean.  aIndian subcontinent.  aIndigenous peoples of the Americas.  aIndonesia.  aJanet Abu-Lughod.  aKarakorum.  aKenneth Pomeranz.  aKuril Islands.  aLaos.  aLighting.  aMa Huan.  aMacau.  aMaghreb.  aMalaysia.  aMaritime history.  aMiddle latitudes.  aMindanao.  aMuslim world.  aNagasaki.  aOpium.  aOrbital speed.  aOxford University Press.  aPhilippines.  aPiracy.  aPlaywright.  aPort.  aQuantity.  aReligious conversion.  aReorient.  aRyukyu Kingdom.  aSanjay Subrahmanyam.  aSea lane.  aSecession.  aShahbandar.  aSlipway.  aSocial structure.  aSouth Asia.  aSouth China Sea.  aSouth India.  aSoutheast Asia.  aSphere of influence.  aSpice trade.  aSujit Sivasundaram.  aSupply chain.  aSurveillance.  aTang dyn